    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-04-03T17:57:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-04-03T17:57:00-05:00" n="82"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d82">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/4–352: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Joint Chiefs of Staff</gloss> to the
                        Commander in Chief United Nations Command (<persName corresp="#p_RGMB1"
                            type="to">Ridgway</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>operational immediate</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-04-03T17:57:00-05:00"
                            >April 3, 1952—5:57 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 905427. From <gloss target="#t_JCS1"
                        >JCS</gloss>. Re Para 5 C 65650<note n="1" xml:id="d82fn1">Dated Mar. 20,
                            <ref target="#pg_109">p. 109</ref>.</note> and part 2 HNC 1118.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d82fn2">Dated Apr. 4, <ref target="#pg_136">p.
                        136</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Alternative position on Soviet Union as mbr Supervisory Commission, if
                        “neutral” designation eliminated and United States is also mbr, as set forth
                        para 2D (1) (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) (<hi rend="italic">1</hi>) <gloss
                            target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss> 903687,<note n="3" xml:id="d82fn3">Dated
                            Mar. 15, <ref target="#pg_89">p. 89</ref>.</note> is in no way
                        considered here as any concession whatever to Commie position on this point.
                        As Soviet Union can introduce Soviet natls into mbrship teams from satellite
                        countries, only real value to Soviets’ overt mbrship on teams is propaganda
                        value of ability to pose in role of “neutral” in Korean hostilities.
                        Suggested alternative, if used, would, of course, be presented in negots by
                            <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> Del as compromise. It might well be
                        so interpreted by international opinion to our consequent advantage. By
                        placing Soviets openly on side of Commie aggressors only real advantage to
                        Soviets of mbrship on inspection commission is destroyed and chances of
                        their acceptance this alternative would appear to be very slight. Thus, it
                        appears here that this alternative offers very advantageous negotiating and
                        propaganda possibilities with minimum of potential disadvantages.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>If, in spite of foregoing considerations, you continue to feel that this
                        alternative proposal should not be presented, you are authorized to proceed
                        according to your best judgment as indicated in para l<hi rend="italic"
                            >b</hi> part 2 HNC 1118. Under these conditions part 2 is
                        approved.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
        </body>
